DEFECTUS. Lat. Defect; default;
want; imperfection; disqualification.
—Challenge propter defectum. A challenge to a juror on account of some legal disqualification, such as infancy, etc. See CIAL-

DEMEMBRATION. In Scotch law.
Maliciously cutting off or otherwise separating one limb from another. 1 Hume, 323;
Bell.

DEMENS. One whose mental faculties
are enfeebled; one who has lost his mind;
distinguishable from amens, one totally insane. 4 Coke, 128.

DEPOSITO. In Spanish law. Deposit;
the species of bailment so called. Schm.
Civil Law, 193.

DESCENDER. In the descent.
See FORFEITURE.


Descent ;

DEXTANS. Lat. In Roman law... A division of the as, consisting of ten unciae;
2 Bl. Comm. 462,
note m. ; ;

DISCONVENABLE. L. Fr.
unfit. Kelham.


Improper;

DISJUNCTIVE TERM. One which is
placed between two contraries, by the affirming of one of which the other is taken away;
it is usually expressed by the word “or.”

DISTRAHERE. To sell; to draw apart;
to dissolve a contract; to divorce. Calvin. -


DISTRAIN

DOMICILIARY. Pertaining to domicile;
relating to one's domicile. Existing or created at, or connected with, the domicile of a
suitor or of a decedent.

DOMITZ. Lat. Tame; domesticated ;
not wild. Applied to domestic animals, in
which a man may have an absolute property. 2 Bl. Comm. 391.

DONUM. Lat. In the civil law. A gift;
a free gift. Calvin. Distinguished from
munus. Dig. 50, 16, 194.
